# Product Rules

- Treat the current app as a desktop-oriented media library prototype focused on `browse -> inspect -> play -> configure`.
- Prioritize the four visible product surfaces: library browsing, detail inspection, player focus, and settings control.
- `library`, `favorites`, `recent`, and `tags` should feel like one continuous browsing experience, not four separate apps.
- Search, tab filters, and selected-movie state are core navigation behavior; preserve them when changing layouts or components.
- Keep the library experience poster-first, compact, and fast to scan; avoid drifting into a table-heavy admin dashboard unless explicitly requested.
- Detail pages should deepen context on one title with clear metadata hierarchy and related content, not generic hero-banner marketing layouts.
- Player pages should remain low-chrome and video-first; controls support playback but should not compete with the media surface.
- Settings should model real library operations such as paths, scan cadence, metadata workflow, playback preferences, and manual maintenance actions.
- Until a real backend exists, new product behaviors should be expressible through typed front-end contracts and mockable data flows.
- When writing or revising docs, always separate `current prototype`, `target desktop product`, and `open decisions`.
